net.akami.mask.core

Class MaskOperatorHandler

  • java.lang.Object
    • net.akami.mask.core.MaskOperatorHandler

  • public class MaskOperatorHandler
extends java.lang.Object
    Highest level object of the operation architecture.

    It corresponds to the manager for the MaskOperator instances. It allows the user to call the compute() methods with the MaskOperator#getClass() type wanted.

    Four data are handled at once by the manager. The first one is the default mask to use whenever the in parameter is not specified through the compute() methods. Setting the default mask's value (by calling begin(Mask)) is optional, though errors will be thrown if compute() is being called without in specified.

    The second one is the calculation environment (MaskContext) to use for every calculation performed through the manager. If no context is specified, MaskContext.DEFAULT will be used.

    The third one is a list of MaskOperators. Those are the operators that are supported by the manager. Most of the time this field doesn't require any modification. You'll only need to modify the list if you want to remove operators to limit the features of the manager, or if you want to modify / add new operators.

    Eventually, the fourth data is a boolean defining whether the out Mask should be set to the default Mask after calls to compute. If set to true, it allows the user to chain operation without having to repeat the in Mask.

    For further information, see compute(Class, Mask, Object), compute(Class, Mask, Mask, Object), compute(Class, Mask, Object, Consumer) and compute(Class, Mask, Mask, Object, Consumer)

      • compute

        public <E,T extends MaskOperator<E>> MaskOperatorHandler compute(java.lang.Class<T> op,
                                                                 Mask out,
                                                                 E extraData)
        Computes a string based on the default mask, according to the operator type given.

        Once the result is computed, the out mask will be reloaded with it through Mask.reload(String).

        If no mask is set as the default in, an error will be thrown. Default masks can be set through begin(Mask), or after any compute() call if setToOut is set to true.

        The extra data corresponds to the additional information required by the operator to work. See MaskOperator for further information.

        Parameters:
        op - the type of the operator
        out - where the result computed will be written
        extraData - extra data required by the operator
        Returns:
        the operator itself for chaining

        Once the result is computed, the out mask will be reloaded with it through Mask.reload(String).
